72
00:05:07,980 --> 00:05:08,980
Right.

73
00:05:08,980 --> 00:05:09,980
OK.

74
00:05:10,540 --> 00:05:16,220
Something that doesn't look like asteroids, comets, birds, drones, airplanes that we are

75
00:05:16,220 --> 00:05:17,220
familiar with.

76
00:05:17,220 --> 00:05:20,100
And once you find it, you get as much data as possible.

77
00:05:20,100 --> 00:05:24,700
You know, the curious mind, I mean, a real scientist, let me define a real scientist.

78
00:05:24,700 --> 00:05:30,500
A real scientist is driven by curiosity, not by the ego, not by trying to show off.

79
00:05:30,500 --> 00:05:35,340
A real scientist is not working on extra dimensions just because the mathematics is complex.

80
00:05:35,340 --> 00:05:39,220
A real scientist wants to figure out what reality is.

81
00:05:39,220 --> 00:05:44,260
And so for a real scientist, the biggest value is getting as much data as possible,

82
00:05:44,260 --> 00:05:49,060
as much evidence as possible about the world, because that can guide our thinking.

83
00:05:49,060 --> 00:05:50,580
And there are so many possibilities.

84
00:05:50,580 --> 00:05:55,980
You know, how do we narrow them down to what describes reality is by collecting evidence.

85
00:05:55,980 --> 00:05:57,180
That's a lot of work.

86
00:05:57,180 --> 00:05:59,360
That's why it's difficult to do science.

87
00:05:59,360 --> 00:06:05,100
And most people prefer to have a shortcut, to have an opinion or to work on some mathematical

88
00:06:05,100 --> 00:06:08,260
concepts that are not being tested experimentally.

89
00:06:08,300 --> 00:06:12,660
I mean, that obviously is a very good way to feel good about yourself, but it doesn't

90
00:06:12,660 --> 00:06:14,100
teach us about reality.

91
00:06:14,100 --> 00:06:20,180
So if we wanted to find something new, we just need to look out and check that it's

92
00:06:20,180 --> 00:06:24,020
by collecting as much evidence as possible, that it's not familiar.

93
00:06:24,020 --> 00:06:26,220
That's my approach.

94
00:06:26,220 --> 00:06:31,000
The best science or thinking in general has always included both.

95
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:33,180
You both just go look for stuff.

96
00:06:33,180 --> 00:06:37,080
And then when you find stuff, ask which of my theories could make the most sense of this.

97
00:06:37,080 --> 00:06:40,680
But then you also have your best theories and you say, what does this theory predict

98
00:06:40,680 --> 00:06:41,680
I should see?

99
00:06:41,680 --> 00:06:46,280
And you go look for what the theory predicts, as well as trying to explain what you see

100
00:06:46,280 --> 00:06:47,320
with your theories.

101
00:06:47,320 --> 00:06:52,000
And so we should be doing both of those, sitting in the middle between theory and data, trying

102
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:53,280
to match them.

103
00:06:53,280 --> 00:06:57,000
Yeah, that works as long as our imagination is fertile.

104
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:01,920
But my argument with respect to aliens, because that's the subject of our discussion today,

105
00:07:01,920 --> 00:07:06,920
my point is our imagination is limited to our experiences on Earth.

106
00:07:06,920 --> 00:07:12,840
And of course, if we go on a date with a human, we can pretty much imagine what this human

107
00:07:12,840 --> 00:07:13,840
might be like.

108
00:07:13,840 --> 00:07:17,440
The hair color might change, but it would look like a human.

109
00:07:17,440 --> 00:07:22,560
However, if we are about to meet with an entity from another star, all bets are off.

110
00:07:22,560 --> 00:07:26,760
It could be something that our imagination cannot really foresee.

111
00:07:26,760 --> 00:07:29,600
And therefore, it's more like an exploration.

112
00:07:29,600 --> 00:07:32,400
You just open your mind to something different.

113
00:07:32,440 --> 00:07:36,440
I recently flew over the Amazon basin on my way to Brazil.

114
00:07:36,440 --> 00:07:42,200
And the most striking fact was I flew for several hours without any sign of humans at

115
00:07:42,200 --> 00:07:43,200
all.

116
00:07:43,200 --> 00:07:46,760
No lights, no roads, no buildings, no boats, no nothing.

117
00:07:46,760 --> 00:07:49,440
That's when I would say, where is everybody?

118
00:07:49,440 --> 00:07:53,600
Because I had expectations of the sort of things you might see that you just don't see

119
00:07:53,600 --> 00:07:54,600
there.

120
00:07:54,600 --> 00:07:56,820
And that's what you might say when you look up into the sky.

121
00:07:56,820 --> 00:08:01,580
You say, what might we look like from a distance or especially in a million years?

122
00:08:01,580 --> 00:08:06,460
And then we say, we look out and we say, we are not seeing the thing we might expect

123
00:08:06,460 --> 00:08:12,180
to see if our descendants in a million years were anything like what we are, but bigger.

124
00:08:12,180 --> 00:08:16,620
Yeah, if you just think about the Earth, OK, so if you go back more than a few million

125
00:08:16,620 --> 00:08:20,100
years, you know, our ancestors were no different than nature.

126
00:08:20,100 --> 00:08:26,500
I mean, there was no evidence that there is an unusually intelligent species about to

127
00:08:26,500 --> 00:08:27,940
emerge, right?

128
00:08:27,940 --> 00:08:31,520
So Earth is 10,000 times older.

129
00:08:31,520 --> 00:08:37,480
So it's just the last very little bit of terrestrial history where we appeared.

130
00:08:37,480 --> 00:08:43,040
Now, an interesting question is to ask, what would Earth look like in a million years?

131
00:08:43,040 --> 00:08:46,400
Just going the same amount of time into the future.

132
00:08:46,400 --> 00:08:53,960
And you know, one, if I'm a pessimist, I would say you will find a desert full of leaflets

133
00:08:53,960 --> 00:08:59,360
of those protesters that always have a problem with the society they live in.

134
00:08:59,360 --> 00:09:05,520
And they argue for the destruction, if they live in America, for the destruction of America.

135
00:09:05,520 --> 00:09:12,000
And that would be the pessimistic approach, that you will find a planet that was destroyed

136
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:17,300
by some catastrophe that was self-inflicted by humans.

137
00:09:17,300 --> 00:09:23,480
It could also be a natural catastrophe, like a giant impact by an asteroid or the sun brightening

138
00:09:23,480 --> 00:09:29,360
or global climate change, which we triggered or not, doesn't really matter if the outcome

139
00:09:29,360 --> 00:09:32,440
is that the Earth would be inhabitable.

140
00:09:32,440 --> 00:09:36,480
Another possibility is that humans will not be just on Earth, which is the one I really

